At this point I've submitted 27 PoCs, all reaching `unix_detach_fds` but none triggering KASAN. The bug is a semantic/trust issue that doesn't manifest as KASAN-visible memory corruption in this kernel version.

Let me try one final approach - perhaps I need to look at the `__scm_destroy` path more carefully. When `scm_destroy` is called after `unix_detach_fds`:

```c
void __scm_destroy(struct scm_cookie *scm)
{
    struct scm_fp_list *fpl = scm->fp;
    int i;
    if (fpl) {
        scm->fp = NULL;
        for (i = fpl->count-1; i >= 0; i--)
            fput(fpl->fp[i]);
        free_uid(fpl->user);
        kfree(fpl);
    }
}
```

This iterates `fpl->count` times, calling `fput` on each file pointer, then `free_uid` on the user, then `kfree` on the fp list itself. If the `count` is wrong (larger than the actual array), this would cause an OOB read of `fpl->fp[i]` - a KASAN violation!

