```

Each PEEK call dups the fp list, which increments the file refcounts. After `scm_detach_fds` or `scm_destroy`, the dup'd fp list is freed (fput on files).

But the ORIGINAL fp list on the skb is NOT modified. So multiple PEEK calls can safely dup the same original fp list multiple times.

What if we PEEK so many times that the file refcount overflows? Each PEEK dup increments refcount (via `get_file`), and each `scm_destroy` decrements it (via `fput`). If we can make `scm_destroy` NOT happen (e.g., by not providing msg_control), then the refcount would keep incrementing.

Wait, but `scm_destroy` is always called at the end of `__scm_recv_common`, regardless of whether msg_control is provided. Let me check:

```c
static inline bool __scm_recv_common(struct socket *sock, struct msghdr *msg,
                     struct scm_cookie *scm, int flags)
{
    if (!msg->msg_control) {
        if (test_bit(SOCK_PASSCRED, &sock->flags) ||
            test_bit(SOCK_PASSPIDFD, &sock->flags) ||
            scm->fp || scm_has_secdata(sock))
            msg->msg_flags |= MSG_CTRUNC;
        scm_destroy(scm);
        return false;
    }
    ...
    if (scm->fp)
        scm_detach_fds(msg, scm);
    return true;
}
```

If `!msg->msg_control`, then `scm_destroy` is called (which fputs files and kfrees the fp list). If `msg->msg_control` is provided, `scm_detach_fds` is called (which installs fds and then calls `__scm_destroy`).

Either way, the dup'd fp list is properly cleaned up. No refcount leak.

